{
  "lesson_id": "lesson_auxiliary_masu",
  "lesson_title": "The Politeness Bit: The Auxiliary ます (masu)",
  "lesson_summary": "This lesson introduces the auxiliary 'masu', which functions as a 'social logic gate' to elevate the tone of a verb, indicating respect or formal politeness toward the subject or the listener.",
  "grammar_point": "auxiliary_masu",
  "grammar_explanation": {
    "concept": "In Classical Japanese, 'masu' (ます) is an auxiliary verb that adds a layer of politeness or honorific respect to the action. Think of it as a 'politeness bit' in a data packet; the core data (the verb's meaning) remains the same, but the 'header' changes how the receiver perceives the tone. It is the ancestor of the modern Japanese polite form.",
    "formation": "It typically attaches to the Ren'yokei (Continuative Form) of verbs.",
    "variations": [
      "ませ (mase) - The Imperative or Subjunctive form, often used in prayers, wishes, or commands to a superior."
    ],
    "common_confusions": [
      "Do not confuse 'masu' with the similar-sounding 'mashi' (counterfactual). 'Masu' is about social register, while 'mashi' is about hypothetical logic."
    ]
  },
  "teaching_sequence": [
    {
      "type": "introduction",
      "content": "Up until now, we have focused on the 'what' and 'when' of actions—negation, past tense, and completion. However, language also carries a 'social vector.' In Classical Japanese, verbs often carry markers to indicate the status of the person performing the action or the person being addressed. The auxiliary <span style='color: #e67e22;'>ます (masu)</span> is the primary tool for this, functioning much like the distinction between '你' (nǐ) and '您' (nín) in Chinese, but applied directly to the verb structure."
    },
